## Chapter 4

### Political Crowd Addiction — The Return After Liberation

Defeat rarely connects well with festivals. Defeat scatters; festivals gather.

### Where Has the Sensation of the Plaza Gone?

For the generation that directly passed through the political struggles of the 1980s, the plaza was never merely an event space. It was a place where people confirmed one another’s existence, where isolated individuals first heard the trembling of their own voices inside a crowd. Danger, exhaustion, and the atmosphere of repression all coexisted there. Because of that, the collective connection carried a density beyond simple excitement.

After democratization, Korea’s political plazas entered a different phase. People no longer needed to risk their lives to gather, yet the desire to assemble did not disappear. Instead, it returned repeatedly in altered forms. Every election season, every major political moment, people once again emerge into the plaza, attempting to recreate the emotional intensity of earlier decades.

I have gradually come to understand this repetitive return as a kind of addiction.

The word may sound too severe. Yet the stronger the experience of collective fervor becomes, the emptier ordinary life can feel once it fades. And so people seek the plaza again, trying to fill that void. This is the basic structure of political crowd addiction.

### Don Quixote’s Pilgrimage Through the Plaza

Cervantes’s Don Quixote is a man so consumed by tales of knight-errantry that he can no longer distinguish reality from fiction. Windmills become giants. Inns become castles. His illusion is not merely madness, but the result of longing for a narrative so intensely that reality reshapes itself to fit it.

Those addicted to political crowds often perceive the world similarly. Every social event becomes absorbed into political narrative. Even neutral incidents are interpreted through camps and ideologies. When the heat of one plaza cools, another is awaited. Everyday life becomes merely an interval between spectacles.

Life outside the plaza begins losing meaning.

Just as Don Quixote ultimately returns, on his deathbed, to the ordinary Alonso Quixano, crowd addiction too eventually demands awakening. Sometimes that awakening arrives through betrayal or disillusionment; sometimes through simple exhaustion.

And after awakening, the real question begins:

Can one still live meaningfully without the plaza?

### Addiction to Voice — Doubting Myself

Perhaps I was never someone who truly created artistic plazas. Perhaps I was simply someone who lingered around them for a long time.

I loved spaces where voices gathered. I watched carefully the moment when one person’s words altered another person’s expression. Yet eventually I began doubting myself. Was I too addicted to the plaza? Had I sought confirmation of my existence only through speech, response, applause, and reaction?

The plaza is always organized around those who speak — or more precisely, those capable of transforming pain and conviction into narrative.

Did I desire that position? Or avoid it? The boundary between the two is often unclear.

Perhaps this is why I cannot easily trust heroic rhetoric. The moment someone speaks “for” the suffering, there is also the danger of absorbing that person’s hesitation and silence into a single explanatory story. Someone stands at the center of the plaza proclaiming history, while someone else remains at the margins, never fully able to shape their feelings into language.

My gaze lingers longer on those awkward silences, those unfinished expressions, those faces unable to fully explain themselves.

