## Chapter 5

### Political Five-Day Markets — The Rationality and Tragedy of Seasonal Plazas

Every election season the plaza opens, and when the votes are counted people disperse again. This rhythm resembles the old Korean five-day market exactly.

### The Temporality of the Five-Day Market

In small towns throughout Korea, markets once opened on fixed dates: the 5th, 10th, 15th, 20th, 25th, 30th. Merchants arrived the day before. By dawn, people gathered. Goods were exchanged, old acquaintances reunited, gossip and news traveled over bowls of makgeolli.

And then, by evening, the market disappeared. The empty field returned until the next market day.

Modern political plazas strangely resemble this rhythm.

During election seasons, plazas become lively. Campaign crowds gather, online arguments intensify, politics fills ordinary conversation. But once voting ends, the plaza dissolves. People return to daily life, political energy sinking back into dormancy until the next cycle.

### The Rationality of Temporariness

This temporary structure should not be understood only negatively. There is a certain rationality within it.

A plaza does not need to remain constantly open. Gathering at the appropriate moment, completing what must be done, then returning to ordinary life may actually represent a healthier form of political participation.

The five-day market endured precisely because it did not operate continuously. The interval managed collective exhaustion. Had the market opened every day, both merchants and customers would eventually have collapsed from fatigue.

Politics functions similarly. Constant political intensity burns people out. Everyday life between elections replenishes exhausted civic energy.

Yet modern political plazas differ from old markets in one crucial respect.

Five-day markets created ongoing relationships. Merchants and regular customers met repeatedly. Familiarity accumulated over time. Modern political plazas often lack such continuity. Different crowds gather each time, and once the event ends, the relationships vanish with it.

A temporary plaza without relationships resembles less a marketplace than a temporary parking lot.

### The Changing Landscape of Elections

Election culture today differs dramatically from earlier eras.

In the past, candidates often stood together at public rallies. Voters compared them directly in shared space. Politics involved physical coexistence.

Now comparison occurs through media fragments instead. People remember politicians less through direct presence than through edited clips, photographs, short videos, camera angles, and crowd reactions.

The plaza still exists, but it increasingly performs for the screen.

At times, the recorded image seems more important than the experience of those actually present there. The plaza’s media representation becomes more powerful than the plaza itself.

