## Chapter 6

### Why the Masses Fail to Become Historical Subjects

The masses are called upon as political subjects, yet ultimately reduced again to isolated individuals.

### The Paradox of Interpellation and Reduction

The word *minjung* — “the people,” “the masses” — carries immense historical weight in Korea. It once named the oppressed, invoked agents of transformation, symbolized collective historical force.

“The people are the protagonists of history.”

This declaration stood at the center of twentieth-century democratic movements.

Yet there is a paradox here. The masses are summoned as political subjects while simultaneously remaining incapable of fully becoming them. Those who shouted together in the plaza return home afterward to confront entirely personal struggles.

There is a vast gap between political invocation and ordinary existence.

Where does this gap originate?

Political language often abstracts human beings. Terms like “citizens,” “the public,” “the people” invoke collective force while erasing individual hesitation, contradiction, and expression. The masses in the plaza are spoken of as though possessing a single will, yet actual lives remain infinitely more fragmented.

### Life Is More Complicated Than Politics

One person worries about survival. Another about family relationships. Another cares more about neighborhood rhythms than ideological struggle. Even those standing in the same plaza arrive there for entirely different reasons.

Political language often simplifies this complexity.

Here lies the paradox of the masses: they become strongest when collectively invoked, yet remain most vulnerable when living as individuals.

And because collective force ultimately emerges from individual human beings who can never fully dissolve into abstraction, the masses are always at risk of dispersal.

Historically this pattern repeats itself. Crowds that once shook history in the plaza eventually return to fragmented private lives afterward. The fruits of collective struggle are rarely distributed equally. The masses become historical subjects only during exceptional moments. In ordinary life, they return once again to being objects rather than agents.

